{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-11-16","name":"Robert de Vieuxpont","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Robert de Vieuxpont","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Robert"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Vieuxpont"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Robert de Veteripont","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1050–1085","fullLifespan":"1050–1085","birthDate":"+1050","birthPlace":{"address":"Vieux Pont, Calvados, Normandie, France","geo":{"latitude":49.25084,"longitude":-0.63097,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1085","deathPlace":{"address":"Sainte Suzanne, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France","@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nRobert De Vipont, aka Robert de Vieuxpont or Robert de Veteri Ponte, was born in 1050 CE at the family's seat in Vieux Pont, pays d'Auge, near Eu, in Calvados, Normandie, France. He was the son of Guillaume (William) de Vieuxpont, part of a Norman aristocratic family, allied with Robert, Duc de Normandie, who was the father of Guillaume le Conquerant (William the Conqueror), the bastard-born Duke of Normandy who gained the title King William I of England when he defeated the Anglo-Saxon King Harald, at the Battle of Hastings in 1066 CE.\n\nRobert de Vieuxpont was a companion to Duke/King William although it's not known if he fought in the 1066 battle (he would have been barely 16 years old). He first appears in the Anglo-Norman records as being charged with the defense La Fleche castle on the Loir River, in Anjou, France around 1073 CE. This was part of William's continental campaigns to consolidate his holdings in western France after conquering England. William must have been happy with Robert de Vieuxpont's service for he gave him rich lands in the north of England and then called upon him to intervene again in France in 1085 CE, to quell another revolt under Angevin Count Fulk and Vicomte Hubert de Beaumont.\n\nNorman nobleman, Robert de Vieuxpont, was killed fighting for William, Duke of Normandy & Conqueror of England (1066) against a Norman rebellion led by Vicomte Hubert de Beaumont, during the siege of the castle of Saint Suzanne in Mayenne, France in 1085.\n\nBirth: 1050 - Calvados, Normandy, Vieux Pont, France\nDeath: 1085 (35) - Normandy, France [sic - Mayenne, Anjou]\nImmediate Family: Son of NN. de Vieuxpont\nHusband of unknown unknown\nFather of Robert de de Vipont, II\nBrother of William de Vipont","sourceList":[{"title":"Legacy NFS Source: William de Veteri-Ponte - ","sourceType":"LEGACY","sourceUri":"MS38-QFY"},{"title":"Legacy NFS Source: William de Veteri-Ponte - ","sourceType":"LEGACY","sourceUri":"MS38-QDY"},{"title":"Legacy NFS Source: William de Veteri-Ponte - ","sourceType":"LEGACY","sourceUri":"MS38-Q8G"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1050","date":"1050","place":"Vieux Pont, Calvados, Normandie, France"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1060","date":"Aft 1060","place":"Calvados, Normandie, France","age":"11","id":"G355-G8Y"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1075","date":"ABT 1075","place":"Aberdour, Fifeshire, Scotland","age":"25","id":"K1T8-CQF"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1085","date":"1085","place":"Vieux, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France","age":"35","id":"GJXP-TGQ"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0","year":"1085","date":"1085","place":"Sainte Suzanne, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France","age":"35"}],"parent":[{"name":"Guillaume de Vieuxpont","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1015–1060","birthDate":"A+1015","deathDate":"+1060/","age":46,"@type":"Person","identifier":"G355-G8Y","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G355-G8Y/guillaume-de-vieuxpont-1015-1060","published":false}],"sibling":[{"name":"Robert de Vieuxpont","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1050–1085","birthDate":"+1050","deathDate":"+1085","age":35,"@type":"Person","identifier":"GW3B-4K3","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GW3B-4K3/robert-de-vieuxpont-10